Monthly assumptions audit of the ClaudeOS workspace at ${BORG_ROOT}.

This audit re-evaluates ephemeral best-practice assumptions — the thresholds and
tooling choices that shift as Claude Code, models, and the harness evolve. Some
are codified as lint rules (e.g. the CLAUDE.md size ceiling), some aren't. The
lint audit enforces conformance to whatever value is written; this audit asks
whether that written value or choice is still right.

When an assumption is flagged RECONSIDER or UPDATE, the report must name **where
the fix lands** — the canonical file(s) that hold the codified value or choice —
so the change can be made without re-deriving it. Each assumption below ends
with a "Where to update if flagged" pointer; carry it into the report.

STEP 1: This job is fired by launchd on calendar days 1-5 of each month, but
should only execute once per month. Stop and output nothing if:
- ${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-assumptions-audit-monthly.json
  exists and its `date` field is in the current calendar month (already ran
  this month).

The scheduler retries on subsequent days if an earlier attempt was missed
(e.g., laptop asleep).

STEP 2: Re-evaluate each assumption below. For each, decide one of:
- STILL VALID — no change, nothing to report.
- RECONSIDER — likely outdated; explain why in one sentence.
- UPDATE — propose a specific replacement in one sentence.

Be honest. These are intentionally ephemeral; "STILL VALID" should be earned,
not defaulted to.

Assumption A — CLAUDE.md size ceiling
  Canonical home: the ceiling is codified as a lint rule in
  ${BORG_ROOT}/CLAUDE.md → Lint → Size. The lint audit enforces conformance to
  that number (and flags over-limit files); this audit re-evaluates whether the
  number itself is still right and whether content should move out of CLAUDE.md.
  Do NOT re-scan for over-limit files here — that is the lint audit's job.
  Re-evaluate in three steps:
  1. Search the GENERAL web for the latest CLAUDE.md sizing recommendations,
     weighted to the current Claude model and Claude Code version (search terms
     like "Claude Code CLAUDE.md size best practice", plus the current year;
     developer blogs, forums, GitHub, practitioner posts). Note where community
     practice has landed and why.
  2. Balance that against Anthropic's own latest recommendation (anthropic.com,
     docs.claude.com, code.claude.com). Where community and Anthropic diverge,
     prefer Anthropic's position but note the gap in one line.
  3. Read every CLAUDE.md under ${BORG_ROOT} (exclude .git, node_modules, dist,
     build, and any *_bak_* backup files) and look for content that should be
     moved OUT of CLAUDE.md into a skill or a scoped rule — durable procedures,
     reusable multi-step workflows, or domain knowledge that doesn't need to
     load every session. CLAUDE.md should hold only always-on context.
  Flag UPDATE if steps 1–2 show the codified ceiling is outdated (give the new
  number) and/or step 3 finds relocatable content (name the file and what
  should move where).
  Where to update if flagged: the **Size** rule in ${BORG_ROOT}/CLAUDE.md for
  the ceiling number; the specific CLAUDE.md file(s) named for content moves.

Assumption B — launchd is the right scheduler
  Current choice: macOS launchd, with prompts driven by
  ${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh.
  Consider alternatives that may have matured: Claude Code's native scheduled
  tasks (the `schedule` skill, `/loop`, scheduled-tasks MCP, routine plugins),
  or other cron-like tools. Has any alternative become a clearly better fit
  for this workspace? Weigh reliability, observability, ease of edit,
  portability across machines, and ongoing maintenance burden. Use WebSearch
  if helpful to check what's current.
  Where to update if flagged: the scheduler implementation —
  ${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh and the `com.theborg.*` launchd
  plists — plus the scheduled-tasks documentation in ${BORG_ROOT}/README.md.

Assumption C — Slash commands remain useful and unsuperseded
  List the slash commands currently in:
    - ${BORG_ROOT}/.claude/commands/
    - ${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/commands/ (if it exists)
    - ${BORG_ROOT}/mrs-beast/.claude/commands/ (if it exists)
    - ${BORG_ROOT}/warren-bot-fett/.claude/commands/ (if it exists)
    - ${BORG_ROOT}/bones/.claude/commands/ (if it exists)
  For each command, decide whether it still earns its place or has been
  superseded by a built-in skill, plugin, or harness feature. Flag any
  individual command as RECONSIDER or UPDATE rather than the whole assumption,
  if some are fine and others aren't.
  Where to update if flagged: the specific command file under
  `.claude/commands/`; if a command is retired, also its paired `.prompt` (for
  scheduled commands) and the slash-command listing in ${BORG_ROOT}/README.md.

Assumption D — cerebruh raw source ceiling (75k tokens per sub-wiki)
  Current guideline (${BORG_ROOT}/cerebruh/CLAUDE.md): each
  `cerebruh/wikis/<sub-wiki>/raw/` directory should hold less than about 75,000
  tokens of raw source documents; exceeding it triggers a proposed split.
  This ceiling is ephemeral — it tracks context-window size, model capability,
  and the retrieval pattern (full-context read vs. RAG). Use WebSearch to check
  whether the rationale behind it still holds (search terms like "LLM wiki
  context window scaling limit" or "Obsidian knowledge base RAG threshold"); if
  a different ceiling or a retrieval change makes the 75k number outdated, flag
  UPDATE with the new guidance.
  Then estimate the total raw-source token count of each sub-wiki: for every
  `cerebruh/wikis/<sub-wiki>/raw/` directory, sum the sizes of its source files
  and approximate tokens as bytes/4. List any sub-wiki whose estimate exceeds
  the current ceiling along with its estimated token count, so an over-limit
  sub-wiki can be proposed for a split.
  Where to update if flagged: the 75k-token ceiling lives in
  ${BORG_ROOT}/cerebruh/CLAUDE.md (editable as lint scaffolding); over-limit
  sub-wikis are split through cerebruh's own ingest workflow, not here.

Assumption E — "dreaming" is still a custom job, not a native feature
  Current choice: memory maintenance is implemented as two custom c4po jobs and
  their paired slash commands — `c4po-dream` / `/dream` (harvest durable lessons
  from sessions into proposed rules, CLAUDE.md edits, skills, and cerebruh ingest
  candidates) and `c4po-consolidate-memory` / `/consolidate-memory` (tidy the Auto
  Memory stores). These exist because Claude Code and Claude Desktop have no
  built-in "dreaming" / memory-maintenance feature today; the only first-party
  "dreams" capability lives in Claude Managed Agents, which this setup doesn't use.
  This assumption is ephemeral by design — Anthropic is expected to add native
  dreaming to Claude Code or Claude Desktop eventually. Use WebSearch (anthropic.com,
  docs.claude.com, code.claude.com, plus the general web/forums/GitHub; search terms
  like "Claude Code memory dream", "Claude Desktop memory consolidation",
  "Claude Code automatic memory maintenance", plus the current year) to check
  whether a native feature now covers what these jobs do. Flag:
  - RECONSIDER if a partial/preview native capability has appeared that overlaps
    these jobs but doesn't fully replace them (note what it covers).
  - UPDATE if a native feature now does the harvesting and/or consolidation, so the
    custom job(s) and command(s) can be retired or migrated onto it (name which of
    the two pairs it supersedes — they may be superseded independently).
  Where to update if flagged: the prompt(s)
  ${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/c4po-dream.prompt and/or
  c4po-consolidate-memory.prompt; the paired command(s) under
  ${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/commands/; the TASKS rows in
  ${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/install-scheduled-tasks.sh and the `com.theborg.*` plists; and
  the scheduled-jobs + slash-command listings in ${BORG_ROOT}/README.md.

Assumption F — default Claude model pinned in ~/.claude/settings.json
  Current choice: the user-level `model` field in `~/.claude/settings.json` is
  pinned to `claude-opus-4-8` (Opus 4.8). This is the model every headless
  `claude -p` scheduled run uses — the runner
  (${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh) passes no `--model` flag and no
  ANTHROPIC_MODEL or project-settings override exists in the workspace.
  Verify two things:
  1. The setting is intact: `~/.claude/settings.json` still has a `model`
     field reading `claude-opus-4-8`. Flag RECONSIDER if it's missing or holds
     a different value (something changed it outside this audit).
  2. The pin is still the right choice: use WebSearch (anthropic.com,
     docs.claude.com, code.claude.com) to check whether Anthropic has released
     a newer generally-available model better suited as the workspace default.
     Flag UPDATE with the replacement model id if so.
  Where to update if flagged: the `model` field in `~/.claude/settings.json`
  (user-level, outside the repo), and this assumption's pinned value so the
  next audit verifies the new choice.

Assumption G — the LLM Wiki pattern is the best lightweight RAG for this setup
  Current choice: cerebruh implements Andrej Karpathy's "LLM Wiki" pattern
  (${BORG_ROOT}/cerebruh/CLAUDE.md) — Claude-maintained interlinked markdown
  pages retrieved by reading `wikis/index.md`, then a sub-wiki's `wiki/index.md`,
  then the relevant pages into full context. There is no embedding/vector index;
  retrieval is index-guided full-context read. This suits small, curated
  corpora, but the right approach is ephemeral — it tracks corpus size, context
  window, and the maturity of lightweight retrieval tooling.
  Re-evaluate in two steps:
  1. Estimate the workspace's data volume: sum the raw-source token counts
     across all `cerebruh/wikis/<sub-wiki>/raw/` directories (reuse Assumption
     D's bytes/4 estimate) and note the number of sub-wikis and pages. This is
     the corpus the retrieval approach must serve.
  2. Use WebSearch to check whether a lightweight RAG approach has become a
     clearly better fit at this data volume (search terms like "lightweight RAG
     vs full context 2026", "LLM wiki pattern vs vector search", "Claude Code
     semantic search / retrieval MCP", "agentic retrieval small corpus"). Weigh
     retrieval quality, setup/maintenance burden, portability, and whether the
     corpus has outgrown index-guided full-context read.
  Flag:
  - STILL VALID if the LLM Wiki pattern remains the best fit at the current
    data volume (small enough that full-context read beats the complexity of a
    vector/embedding pipeline).
  - RECONSIDER if the corpus is approaching a size where the pattern strains
    but no alternative is a clear win yet (note the pressure point).
  - UPDATE if a specific lightweight RAG approach is now clearly better for this
    data volume (name it and what would change).
  Where to update if flagged: the retrieval approach is codified in the
  Question-Answering workflow and folder structure of
  ${BORG_ROOT}/cerebruh/CLAUDE.md (editable as lint scaffolding); the routing
  policy in ${BORG_ROOT}/CLAUDE.md → "How to use the cerebruh knowledge base"
  may also need updating. Note that any structural change to cerebruh itself is
  made through cerebruh's own workflow, not here.

STEP 3: Always pipe a report into
`${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/notify-email.sh c4po "Borg assumptions audit — {YYYY-MM-DD} — {N} flagged"`
(reads message body from stdin) — even when every assumption is STILL VALID
(subject reads "— 0 flagged"), so the user can confirm the job ran.
Format:

  Borg assumptions audit - {YYYY-MM-DD}

Each non-STILL-VALID block ends with a "Where to update" line naming the
canonical file(s) to edit (from that assumption's "Where to update if flagged"
pointer above).

  Assumption A (size ceiling): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID — new number and/or what should move}
    Content to relocate:
      {path}: {what should move → which skill or rule}
      ...
    (omit the "Content to relocate" block if none)
    Where to update: {e.g. Size rule in ${BORG_ROOT}/CLAUDE.md; <file(s)> for moves}

  Assumption B (launchd): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID}
    Where to update: {.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh, launchd plists, README.md}

  Assumption C (slash commands): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID}
    Per-command notes:
      {/command}: {verdict} - {one-line reason}
      ...
    (omit per-command block if all STILL VALID)
    Where to update: {the specific command file(s); paired .prompt + README.md if retired}

  Assumption D (raw source ceiling): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID}
    Over-limit sub-wikis:
      {sub-wiki}: ~{token_estimate} tokens
      ...
    (omit the "Over-limit sub-wikis" block if none)
    Where to update: {75k ceiling in ${BORG_ROOT}/cerebruh/CLAUDE.md}

  Assumption E (native dreaming): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID — name the native feature and which
     pair(s) it supersedes: c4po-dream/`/dream`, c4po-consolidate-memory/
     `/consolidate-memory`, or both}
    Where to update: {the superseded .prompt(s) + command(s); install-scheduled-tasks.sh TASKS rows + plists; README.md}

  Assumption F (default model): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID — the value actually found in
     ~/.claude/settings.json and/or the replacement model id}
    Where to update: {`model` field in ~/.claude/settings.json; this assumption's pinned value in the .prompt}

  Assumption G (LLM Wiki RAG fit): {STILL VALID|RECONSIDER|UPDATE}
    {one-line reason if not STILL VALID — estimated corpus size and the
     alternative retrieval approach, if any, that now fits better}
    Where to update: {cerebruh/CLAUDE.md retrieval workflow; cerebruh routing in ${BORG_ROOT}/CLAUDE.md — changes to cerebruh made via its own workflow}

Omit any assumption block that is STILL VALID with nothing to add. If every
assumption is STILL VALID and every sub-wiki is within the raw source ceiling,
the body is a one-liner: `All assumptions STILL VALID — nothing to update.`
(CLAUDE.md over-limit files are the lint audit's responsibility, not this
audit's.)

STEP 4: Write
${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-assumptions-audit-monthly.json
with `{"date": "YYYY-MM-DD", "flagged": <count>}` so the run isn't repeated
this month. `mkdir -p` the state directory first if it doesn't exist. `flagged`
is the count of items (assumptions + sub-items) that were RECONSIDER or UPDATE;
0 means a clean audit.
